-- Adidas, Allianz, BMW, Draegerwerk, Fielmann, Merck: German Equity Preview
-- Adam Ewing
-- 2010-04-23T06:26:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-23/adidas-allianz-fielmann-merck-kgaa-may-be-active-german-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of
companies whose shares may have unusual price changes in
Germany. Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are
from the previous close.  
 The benchmark DAX Index fell 1 percent to 6,168.72
yesterday.  
 Adidas AG (ADS GY): The world’s second-largest sporting-
goods maker said first-quarter profit jumped on sales of World
Cup soccer-themed items and raised its earnings forecasts for
the year. Adidas shares increased 0.7 percent to 42.82 euros.  
 Allianz SE (ALV GY): Europe’s biggest insurer was cut to
“sell” from “buy” at DZ Bank AG. The stock lost 2 percent to
89.07 euros.  
 Bayerische Motoren Werke AG (BMW GY): It raised its 2010
China sales target to 120,000 units from an earlier 100,000
units, Chief Executive Officer Norbert Reithofer told reporters
today at the Beijing Auto Show. The automaker sees long-term
potential for the Chinese market at sales of about 300,000
vehicles a year. The shares slipped 0.9 percent to 36.25 euros.  
 Draegerwerk AG & Co. KGaA (DRW3 GY): The company said it
expects to achieve an earnings-before-interest-and-taxes margin
in the upper end of its forecast range of 5 to 6 percent
following “extraordinarily positive” earnings in the first
quarter. The shares rose 1.2 percent to 49.33 euros.  
 Fielmann AG (FIE GY): Europe’s largest chain of optical
stores was downgraded to “underperform” from “outperform” at
CA Cheuvreux. Fielmann slid 1.4 percent to 58.07 euros.  
 Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG (HDD GY): The German
printing-press maker said it aims to break even in its operating
business in the next financial year as it cuts costs and the
economy recovers. The shares slumped 4.7 percent to 5.34 euros.  
 Merck KGaA (MRK GY): Lenders to Merck, the German
drugmaker, finished syndicating a 1 billion-euro ($1.3 billion)
loan used to pay for its acquisition of Millipore Corp. The
shares added 2.1 percent to 63.13 euros.  
 Solarworld AG (SWV GY), SMA Solar Technology AG (S92 GY)
and Q-Cells SE (QCE GY): The German government agreed on plans
to slash subsidies for solar energy, sticking to the main points
the Cabinet had agreed on earlier, Reuters reported today,
citing unidentified officials. Solarworld lost 0.6 percent to
11.435 euros, while SMA fell 1.3 percent to 89.93 euros and Q-
Cells slipped 1.5 percent to 7.606 euros.  
